{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613548"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:37:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:37:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16318"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16318"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.04,0.23,0.58,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9009"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116131"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9009"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16318"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98127"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1992"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7244"},{"type":"tags","id":"7508"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21438"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21443"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116131"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe bony orbit houses and protects the eye and its associated structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bones contributes to the formation of the bony orbit?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Temporal bone","Mandible","Nasal bone","Zygomatic bone","Parietal bone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ezygomatic bone\u003C/strong\u003E forms part of the lateral wall of the orbit. The seven bones that form the orbit are the frontal, sphenoid, ethmoid, lacrimal, maxilla, zygomatic, and palatine bones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etemporal bone\u003C/strong\u003E does not contribute to the orbit formation, though it articulates with the zygomatic bone laterally. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emandible\u003C/strong\u003E is the lower jaw bone and has no connection to the orbit. The \u003Cstrong\u003Enasal bone\u003C/strong\u003E forms the bridge of the nose but does not extend to the orbit, whilst the \u003Cstrong\u003Eparietal bone\u003C/strong\u003E forms part of the cranial vault and does not contribute to the orbit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe bony orbit is shaped like a four-sided pyramid with its apex pointing posteromedially. This arrangement provides protection for the eye while allowing passage of the optic nerve and blood vessels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The bony orbit is formed by seven bones: frontal, sphenoid, ethmoid, lacrimal, maxilla, zygomatic, and palatine.","The temporal bone does not contribute to the formation of the orbit."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press.","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98127"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16318"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[